 ('17', '26', '10', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Assignment 1\",\"slug\":\"assignment-1\",\"postDate\":1381663861,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Each group member to evaluate the mockups from Task 1c using one of the following methods:<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n<li>Usability test (with at least 2 users)<\\/li><li>Heuristic analysis (with at least 2 experts) using the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.useit.com\\/papers\\/heuristic\\/heuristic_list.html\\\">10 usability heuristics<\\/a> or the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/designingwebinterfaces.com\\/6-tips-for-a-great-flex-ux-part-5\\\">web application heuristics<\\/a>.<\\/li><li>Controlled experiment (with at least 2 users)<\\/li><\\/ul><p>To evaluate the mockups, you need to:<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n<li>Print your mockups<\\/li><li>Prepare your mockups for the evaluation if necessary, such as interactive elements like radio buttons, pop-up boxes, etc.<\\/li><li>Prepare any additional material needed for the study, such as task lists<\\/li><li>Recruit participants (NB: People from your class qualify as experts, but not as users<\\/li><\\/ul><p>Additionally you should conduct a short post-evaluation interview with your users or experts to find out about their general attitude towards your application concept, what things they liked about, what they didn\\u2019t, whether they were missing any features, etc.<\\/p><p>The minimum requirement is to evaluate the desktop version of your application, but you might want to include the mobile version as well to get early feedback from users\\/experts on this part as well.<\\/p><p><strong>Submission<\\/strong><br>Individual or group blog post describing, including the following:<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n<li>Short description of method<\\/li><li>Description of evaluation procedure, including the number of people tested and what their demographics are, such as age, profession, etc.<\\/li><li>One or more photos of your evaluation session. To respect the privacy of your participants take the photos from an angle in which their face isn\\u2019t visible.<\\/li><li>Findings: what were the main results of the evaluation as well as the post-evaluation interview<\\/li><li>Suggestions for improvements to the interface based on the findings<\\/li><\\/ul><p>The blog post submission is due on <del>Thursday 13 September<\\/del> Sunday 16 September, 8pm. (There is no Blackboard submission.)<\\/p><p>The next task \\u2014 to develop the interactive prototype \\u2014 is due 11 October.<\\/p><p><strong>Resources<\\/strong><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/web.arch.usyd.edu.au\\/~mtomitsch\\/teaching\\/2012\\/deco2200\\/material\\/Designbrief.pdf\\\">Design brief<\\/a> (pdf)<br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.useit.com\\/papers\\/heuristic\\/heuristic_evaluation.html\\\">How to conduct a heuristic evaluation<\\/a><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/designingwebinterfaces.com\\/6-tips-for-a-great-flex-ux-part-5\\\">10 heuristics in web applications<\\/a><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.useit.com\\/papers\\/heuristic\\/heuristic_list.html\\\">Nielsen\\u2019s 10 usability heuristics<\\/a><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.useit.com\\/alertbox\\/20000319.html\\\">Why you only need to test with 5 users<\\/a><br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/dschool.stanford.edu\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2011\\/03\\/BootcampBootleg2010v2SLIM.pdf\\\">d.school bootcamp bootleg\\u2028<\\/a> (pdf) \\u2014 see pages 34 and 35<br><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.ok-cancel.com\\/\\\">OK\\/Cancel<\\/a> \\u2014 comics on usability and human computer interaction<\\/p><p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.userfocus.co.uk\\/articles\\/index.html\\\" style=\\\"font-family: Arial, Helvetica, Verdana, Tahoma, sans-serif;\\\">User Focus<\\/a> \\u2014 articles and resources\\u2028 for further reading<\\/p>\",\"11\":\"\",\"3\":[\"new:Heuristic Evaluation\",\"new:Usability\",\"new:User Focus\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 11:31:01', '2013-10-13 11:31:01', '704f6a9b-107f-4dfd-9e81-d3ba99384ce0'),
