 ('20', '17', '10', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Interaction Design Item\",\"slug\":\"interaction-design-item\",\"postDate\":1381650600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Some people have run into an issue with their BB10 app looking oversized when they tested on the actual device. This is because the BB10 has a high pixel density ratio and web content seems to be rendered by default at a low dpi. The effect is that all of the elements in your app look enlarged. <em>Note that this only happens when you explicitly set the width and height css elements on the &lt;body&gt; to 768px and 1280px respectively.<\\/em><\\/p><p>For most people who have not set the width and height of their &lt;body&gt; or any elements it contains to a certain pixel value and have instead set them to either 100% or just let the elements fill the space, this enlargement issue won\\u2019t happen. What will happen is that your app will render at about 160 pixels per inch. The BB10 however is capable of a resolution of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/developer.blackberry.com\\/devzone\\/design\\/devices_and_screen_sizes.html\\\">356 ppi<\\/a>. That means you are missing out on utilising the full resolution of the device and making a really great looking app.<\\/p><p>The solution is to adjust the \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag slightly. Usually we have had an attribute called \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d that we set to 1.0 meaning that the app is neither zoomed in or out. To adjust for the higher pixel density in the BB10 we want to zoom out slightly. This means setting the \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d to about 0.446.<\\/p><p>So your \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag should now look like this:<\\/p><p>&lt;meta name=\\u201dviewport\\u201d content=\\u201dwidth=device-width,initial-scale=0.446,user-scalable=no\\u201d&gt;<\\/p><p>You may have to adjust your html elements to suit the new resolution of your app. However it will be worth the effort when you end up with a much better looking app.<\\/p><p><strong>Reference:<\\/strong> <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/supportforums.blackberry.com\\/t5\\/Web-and-WebWorks-Development\\/How-to-set-up-the-viewport-for-a-BlackBerry-WebWorks-application\\/ta-p\\/1943807\\\">How to set up the viewport for a BlackBerry WebWorks application for BlackBerry 10<\\/a><\\/p>\",\"5\":\"Design Computing\",\"7\":[\"22\"],\"3\":[\"18\"],\"8\":[\"Interaction Design\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 13:28:04', '2013-10-13 13:28:04', '6ee713c4-d8d2-4a4a-91b8-ea69ab79c01c'),
 ('21', '17', '10', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Making your BB10 app high resolution\",\"slug\":\"interaction-design-item\",\"postDate\":1381650600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Some people have run into an issue with their BB10 app looking oversized when they tested on the actual device. This is because the BB10 has a high pixel density ratio and web content seems to be rendered by default at a low dpi. The effect is that all of the elements in your app look enlarged. <em>Note that this only happens when you explicitly set the width and height css elements on the &lt;body&gt; to 768px and 1280px respectively.<\\/em><\\/p><p>For most people who have not set the width and height of their &lt;body&gt; or any elements it contains to a certain pixel value and have instead set them to either 100% or just let the elements fill the space, this enlargement issue won\\u2019t happen. What will happen is that your app will render at about 160 pixels per inch. The BB10 however is capable of a resolution of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/developer.blackberry.com\\/devzone\\/design\\/devices_and_screen_sizes.html\\\">356 ppi<\\/a>. That means you are missing out on utilising the full resolution of the device and making a really great looking app.<\\/p><p>The solution is to adjust the \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag slightly. Usually we have had an attribute called \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d that we set to 1.0 meaning that the app is neither zoomed in or out. To adjust for the higher pixel density in the BB10 we want to zoom out slightly. This means setting the \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d to about 0.446.<\\/p><p>So your \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag should now look like this:<\\/p><p>&lt;meta name=\\u201dviewport\\u201d content=\\u201dwidth=device-width,initial-scale=0.446,user-scalable=no\\u201d&gt;<\\/p><p>You may have to adjust your html elements to suit the new resolution of your app. However it will be worth the effort when you end up with a much better looking app.<\\/p><p><strong>Reference:<\\/strong> <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/supportforums.blackberry.com\\/t5\\/Web-and-WebWorks-Development\\/How-to-set-up-the-viewport-for-a-BlackBerry-WebWorks-application\\/ta-p\\/1943807\\\">How to set up the viewport for a BlackBerry WebWorks application for BlackBerry 10<\\/a><\\/p>\",\"5\":\"Design Computing\",\"7\":[\"22\"],\"3\":[\"18\"],\"8\":[\"Interaction Design\"],\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-13 13:28:27', '2013-10-13 13:28:27', '6fa3992c-366d-4ab2-9b3f-f584ed3d1749'),
